---
/** Scenario: severance and unemployment at the same time. */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const faqItems = [
  { q: `Will taking severance disqualify me from unemployment?`, a: `Generally no — being laid off (not fired for cause) keeps you eligible. Severance may delay or reduce the benefit in some states, but it rarely disqualifies you outright.` },
  { q: `Do I have to report severance when I file?`, a: `Yes. Report it honestly on your claim; the agency decides how it's treated. Failing to report it can create an overpayment you'll have to repay, sometimes with penalties.` },
];
---

<Base
  title="Severance and unemployment at the same time (2026)"
  description="Can you collect unemployment while getting severance? Often yes — but some states delay or reduce benefits while severance is paid. When you file matters."
  faqItems={faqItems}
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 · scenario</p>
    <h1>Severance and unemployment at the same time</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Can you collect both? Usually yes — but the timing is a real-money decision, because some states pause or reduce unemployment while severance is being paid.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Getting a severance package doesn't automatically disqualify you from unemployment — but the two interact, and how
    they interact depends entirely on your state. In some states, severance is treated like wages and delays or
    reduces your weekly benefit for the weeks it covers. In others, severance is ignored and you can claim unemployment
    from the moment you're out of work. That difference can be worth thousands, which is why <em>when</em> you file is
    a decision worth getting right.
  </p>

  <h2>The two ways states handle it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Severance delays or offsets benefits.</strong> The state allocates your severance over a number of
      weeks and treats it as income, so your unemployment is reduced (often to $0) for those weeks. You claim after the
      severance period ends.</li>
    <li><strong>Severance is ignored.</strong> The state doesn't count severance against unemployment, so you can
      claim right away and collect both at once.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Because this varies so much, our calculators flag it per state rather than guessing — check your state's page and
    confirm with the agency before you file. Filing in the wrong week can forfeit benefits you were entitled to, or
    trigger an overpayment you have to pay back.</p>

  <h2>A practical sequence</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Read your severance agreement — is it a lump sum or paid over weeks? Lump sums are often allocated to a single
      period; continued salary can offset benefits for longer.</li>
    <li>Check your state's rule on your <a href="/unemployment-benefits-calculator/">unemployment page</a>.</li>
    <li>File as soon as you're eligible if your state ignores severance; wait until the severance period ends if it
      offsets. When unsure, file and let the agency determine it — but ask first.</li>
    <li>Fold both income streams into your <a href="/layoff-runway-calculator/">runway</a>.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  {faqItems.map((f) => (
    <div class="faq">
      <h3>{f.q}</h3>
      <p data-review="legal" set:html={f.a}></p>
    </div>
  ))}

  <h2>Your layoff toolkit</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/severance-pay-tax-calculator/">Severance pay tax</a></li>
    <li><a href="/unemployment-benefits-calculator/">Unemployment benefits</a></li>
    <li><a href="/layoff-runway-calculator/">Layoff runway</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">General information for 2026, not legal advice — your state agency determines eligibility and treatment.</p>
</Base>
